GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 863
Short Title: Disaster Recovery Act of 2025 - Part 1(b). (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Prather, Ager, and Turner (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Appropriations, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 10, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO APPROPRIATE FUNDS TO STATE AGENCIES FOR HURRICANE HELENE
3 UNMET NEEDS FOR DISASTER RECOVERY IN WESTERN NORTH CAROLINA.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5
6 PART I. APPROPRIATIONS FOR WESTERN NORTH CAROLINA HURRICANE
7 HELENE RECOVERY
8 SECTION 1. There is appropriated from the Savings Reserve established in
9 G.S. 143C-4-2 the sum of five hundred eighty-two million two hundred twenty-nine thousand
10 seven hundred fifty dollars ($582,229,750) in nonrecurring funds for the 2025-2026 fiscal year
11 to provide funds for unmet needs from Hurricane Helene, as follows:
12 (1) One hundred seven million dollars ($107,000,000) to the Department of
13 Commerce for the following purposes:
14 a. One hundred million dollars ($100,000,000) to Appalachian
15 Community Capital Corporation in partnership with the Dogwood
16 Health Trust for a grant program in accordance with Part III of this act.
17 b. Seven million dollars ($7,000,000) to the Rural Economic
18 Development Division for the Creating Outdoor Recreation
19 Economies (CORE) Program.
20 (2) One hundred five million dollars ($105,000,000) to the Housing Finance
21 Agency for the following purposes:
22 a. Fifty million dollars ($50,000,000) for affordable housing grants to
23 units of local government in the affected area to incentivize
24 high-quality, resilient, affordable housing. This funding may also be
25 used by recipients to repair rental units and shelters for disaster
26 victims. Each unit of local government may apply for a grant not to
27 exceed one million dollars ($1,000,000).
28 b. Twenty-five million dollars ($25,000,000) for homeowner and renter
29 unmet needs, including immediate minor repairs and needs that are not
30 FEMA-eligible.
31 c. Twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) for mortgage and utility
32 assistance.
33 d. Ten million dollars ($10,000,000) for housing stabilization services
34 and financial assistance for homeless populations.
