14 Water Conservation for streambank stabilization and stream
15 restoration.
16 b. Twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) to divide equally among food
17 banks in the affected area. Of these funds, ten million dollars
18 ($10,000,000) shall be used to buy food from local farms.
19 c. Sixteen million seventy-three thousand five hundred dollars
20 ($16,073,500) for the Forest Service for fire season preparation,
21 including equipment, and on-call and overtime pay.
22 d. Twelve million five hundred thousand dollars ($12,500,000) to the
23 Agricultural Development and Farmland Preservation Trust Fund for
24 working farms and forest preservation.
25 e. Three million three hundred fifty thousand dollars ($3,350,000) to the
26 North Carolina Forest Service for new hand crew units for wildfire risk
27 reduction for one year of program operation.
28 f. Five hundred thousand dollars ($500,000) to the Community
29 Conservation Assistance Program for stormwater control in the French
30 Broad River watershed, consistent with the requirements of Article 73
31 of Chapter 106 of the General Statutes.
32 (6) Thirty-nine million two hundred thousand dollars ($39,200,000) to the
33 Department of Public Instruction for the following purposes:
34 a. Fourteen million dollars ($14,000,000) to each community college in
35 the affected area for small business centers. Each community college
36 shall receive one million dollars ($1,000,000) under this allocation.
37 b. Twenty-five million two hundred thousand dollars ($25,200,000) for
38 K-12 Summer Learning Programs to support 30 days of summer
39 instruction in the affected area.
40 (7) Twenty-six million dollars ($26,000,000) to the Office of State Budget and
41 Management for the following purposes:
42 a. Twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) for OSBM to allocate to State
43 agencies for continuing operations and staffing, including The
44 University of North Carolina System.
45 b. Three million dollars ($3,000,000) for directed grants to Legal Aid of
46 North Carolina, Inc., a nonprofit corporation, and Pisgah Legal
47 Services, a nonprofit corporation, for disaster legal services for those
48 affected by Hurricane Helene.
49 c. Three million dollars ($3,000,000) for North Carolina independent
50 colleges and universities in the affected area damaged by Hurricane
51 Helene.
